{"summary":"Accepted the snapshot-read observability amendment and rejected the documentation-only and unsafe legacy-backfill amendments. The code should distinguish missing snapshots from real read/corruption failures, already enforces the journal-schema contract through failing tests, and correctly avoids guessing historical `plan_hash` values for legacy rows.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-4-0dab1450","decision":"accept","rationale":"`FsTaskRunLineageStore::snapshot_plan_hash()` currently uses `read_snapshot(...).ok().and_then(...)`, so `NotFound`, corrupt `status.json`, and permission failures all collapse to `None`. That silently disables `plan_hash` auto-population with no operator signal and makes real storage errors indistinguishable from the benign \"no snapshot yet\" case. Logging or tracing non-`NotFound` failures is a low-risk observability fix that preserves current fallback behavior while surfacing genuine corruption or access problems."},{"amendment_id":"fr-4-e29e2ea2","decision":"reject","rationale":"The implementation already satisfies the stated \"test failure\" requirement. `#[serde(deny_unknown_fields)]` makes the parser reject unexpected fields at runtime, and the round-trip tests in `src/adapters/fs.rs` call `parse(...).expect(...)` on model-rendered JSON, so adding a rendered field without updating the parsing struct already produces a failing test. The test comments already explain that these checks keep the parser and renderer in sync, so an extra doc comment or `CLAUDE.md` note is optional documentation rather than a concrete correctness, safety, or maintainability defect."},{"amendment_id":"fr-4-e57cd3d1","decision":"reject","rationale":"This amendment assumes the current snapshot hash can safely repair older rows whose `plan_hash` was never recorded, but the code explicitly guards against that because the snapshot may have advanced after the original attempt started. In that case, stamping the current `snapshot.plan_hash` would mislabel a historical run with a newer plan version. Existing backfill paths already repair `plan_hash` when the caller supplies a concrete value; what they intentionally avoid is snapshot-based guessing for legacy `null` rows. Keeping `null` as \"unknown\" is safer than writing a potentially wrong hash, and the new regression tests correctly enforce that invariant."}]}